Otto Gessler, who served as Defense Minister for eight years following Noske’s departure and preceding Groener, is a conservative and a <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span> by reason rather than conviction—often at odds with his colleagues in the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**DDP**</span> throughout his tenure. He made little effort to reform the Reichswehr and played an active role in the <i>Reichsexekution</i> against our United Left governments in Saxony and Thuringia during the German October. Now, after stepping away from politics in early 1928, he seeks a return to the national stage.

His candidacy is supported by the [? if not lvp_formed: <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>?][? if lvp_formed: <span style="color: #FFCC00;">**LVP**</span>?]. [? if not lvp_formed: He is also nominally supported by the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span>, which has grown more right-wing and more accepting over the years. ?]

- @harzburg: We await the decision of the Harzburg Front.

@adenauer
