By some miracle for the German Right, they have managed to persuade Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck—renowned for his successful guerrilla campaign in German East Africa during the Great War—to run for the presidency. However, the circumstances now are far more dire than they were in 1925. The German Right is significantly less unified behind Lettow-Vorbeck than it had been for President Hindenburg.

How Lettow-Vorbeck would govern remains uncertain. It is highly likely that, much like Hindenburg, a camarilla of close advisors would shape his decisions from behind the scenes.

His candidacy is backed by the [? if not vorbeck_fallback: [? if dnvp_ideology == "Radical": <span style="color: #0087DC;">**KVP**</span>?][? if dnvp_ideology == "Moderate": <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>?], along with a disparate coalition of minor bourgeois parties. ?][? if vorbeck_fallback: entirety of the Bürgerblock parties, who view him as their collective last hope at retaining power. ?]

- @harzburg: We await the decision of the Harzburg Front.

