Kuno von Westarp, a familiar figure in German politics, has long been a stalwart of the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, once serving as both party leader and head of its parliamentary group. While not entirely opposed to his party’s participation in a <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span> system, he has made no secret of his monarchist aspirations. His rigid partisanship and staunchly anti-<span style="color: #c00000;">socialist</span> convictions are likely to define his rule—perhaps even making him a more hostile figure than Hindenburg.

It is imperative that we prevail over these forces of reaction if we are to have any hope of returning to government.

His candidacy is backed by the [? if dnvp_ideology == "Radical": <span style="color: #0087DC;">**KVP**</span>?][? if dnvp_ideology == "Moderate": <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>?], along with a disparate coalition of minor bourgeois parties.

- @harzburg: We await the decision of the Harzburg Front.

